## SECTION 2 — CURRENT FEATURES (EXHAUSTIVE)
════════════════════════════════════════

### Fan Dashboard (Live Event Hub)
├── **What it does:** Displays a personalized, real-time interface for a fan during an event. It shows ticket details (Gate, Seat), a live AreaChart of stadium-wide crowd density (North, South, East, West gates), a BarChart of predicted wait times at various entrances, and an AI recommendation panel suggesting the best gate or concession stand.
├── **Why it was built:** Fans need actionable, immediate data to avoid long lines and navigate the stadium efficiently, improving their overall experience.
├── **How it works technically:** React frontend connects via authenticated REST API to fetch ticket details and AI recommendations. It concurrently maintains a WebSocket connection (`/api/ws/crowd/{eventId}`) to the FastAPI backend, receiving updated crowd density arrays every 3 seconds to re-render the Recharts components smoothly.
├── **Inputs/Outputs:** Inputs: User Firebase Auth token, Event ID. Outputs: Rendered UI with dynamic charts, active ticket status, and text-based navigation recommendations.
├── **Edge cases:** WebSocket disconnection drops the real-time feed; gracefully falls back to showing a "Syncing live data..." state or standard HTTP polling data if available. Fails if user lacks a valid ticket for the event.
├── **UI/UX flow:** User views event list -> selects active event -> enters Dashboard. The UI features a dark, neon-accented God-mode aesthetic with live-updating modular cards.
└── **What breaks if removed:** The core fan experience is destroyed. Fans revert to being blind to stadium conditions.

### Host Security Panel (Dashboard)
├── **What it does:** Provides stadium operators a unified command center. Features a simulated 2x3 CCTV camera grid with AI threat-scanning overlays, a live crowd density map, and a real-time security alert feed (with severity color-coding and unread badges). Allows hosts to manually generate and broadcast alerts.
├── **Why it was built:** Security and operations teams need a single pane of glass to monitor the entire venue, receive automated threat detections, and communicate instantly with staff and fans.
├── **How it works technically:** Similar to the Fan dashboard, it uses WebSockets (`/api/ws/crowd/{eventId}` and `/api/ws/alerts/{eventId}`) for real-time density and alert streaming. The FastAPI backend `simulation.py` service continuously calculates density states and randomly generates context-aware alerts (e.g., "Critical Overcrowding at Gate B" if density > 85%). Manual alert generation posts to a REST endpoint which saves to Firestore.
├── **Inputs/Outputs:** Inputs: Host Auth & Event ID verification. Manual alert creation payload (title, description, severity). Outputs: High-density data visualizations, ringing visual alerts, and a manual alert form.
├── **Edge cases:** High volume of alerts could cause UI lag (currently mitigated by limiting the stored/displayed alert history). Unverified hosts attempting access receive a 403 Forbidden.
├── **UI/UX flow:** Host logs in -> Selects assigned event -> Enters Dashboard. The UI prioritizes visual hierarchy, drawing immediate attention to red "Critical" alerts and high-density heat map spikes.
└── **What breaks if removed:** Venue operators lose their operational overview, rendering the smart stadium concept useless from a management perspective.

### Simulated AI Analytics Engine
├── **What it does:** Generates realistic, fluctuating data for crowd densities, wait times, and contextual security alerts without requiring physical hardware sensors.
├── **Why it was built:** To provide a fully functional, demonstrable MVP of the NexArena concept for hackathons and pitches before deploying real physical IoT infrastructure.
├── **How it works technically:** The `simulation.py` module in FastAPI uses mathematical models (sinusoidal curves + Gaussian noise offset by a specific phase shift per stadium gate) to simulate organic crowd breathing/movement over time. It scales these densities into wait-time predictions. The `alert_generator` routinely checks these densities; if a gate exceeds 85%, it forces a "Critical Overcrowding" alert. Otherwise, it pulls from a pool of generic stadium events (lost child, VIP arrival).
├── **Inputs/Outputs:** Inputs: Event ID (to maintain consistent state per event). Outputs: Dicts of gate densities (0-100%), wait times (minutes), and alert payloads.
├── **Edge cases:** Over extended uptime, the sinusoidal math might synchronize unnaturally without enough random seed jitter (mitigated by time_factor offsets).
├── **UI/UX flow:** Invisible to the user; operates entirely backend.
└── **What breaks if removed:** The entire application becomes static. Charts turn flat, webhooks send zero data, and the platform appears dead.

### Role-Based Authentication & Verification
├── **What it does:** Segregates users into 'Fan' or 'Host' roles using Firebase Authentication, restricting access to respective dashboards.
├── **Why it was built:** Security and privacy. Fans cannot see camera feeds or trigger evacuation alerts; hosts don't need a personalized "My Ticket" view.
├── **How it works technically:** React UI wraps routes in a `<ProtectedRoute>` component. `AuthContext.tsx` manages Firebase state and syncs with the FastAPI `/api/me` endpoint to persist the user's role ("host" or "fan") directly into Firestore.
├── **Inputs/Outputs:** Inputs: Email/Password login, user-selected role at signup, Firebase JWT tokens. Outputs: Secured syncing of user roles into the database, caching to `localStorage`, and React Router `Navigate` redirects to appropriate dashboards.
├── **Edge cases:** If the backend verification fails (like a 404 during a new Cloud Run deployment transition), the system robustly falls back to local state memory, ensuring no user gets blocked from legitimate signup or login routing.
├── **UI/UX flow:** User hits `/login` -> Toggle Fan/Host -> Resolves Role -> Redirects cleanly to `/events` (Fan) or `/host/events` (Host).
└── **What breaks if removed:** Complete security failure. Role management dictates dashboard access dynamically.


